Yield Farming

A Lending Renaissance
Kinji Steimetz

May 17, 2024 ⋅  19 min read

This report was originally published as an Enterprise tier report on Mar 12, 2024

Key Insights

  • Gearbox presents 50% upside by tackling the deficiencies in existing DeFi lending protocols. This presents an opportunity to seize market share and foster overall market growth.
  • Integrations with Liquid Restaking Tokens (LRT) have been a driving force behind the growth of undercollateralized lending protocols. In a bullish market, this momentum is expected to persist, fueled by further LRT adoption, tokenized carry trades, and a growth in yield farming.
  • While growth constraints exist for undercollateralized lending, they are somewhat overstated.

Introduction to Onchain Lending

DeFi seems to have faded into the background of the crypto landscape, as investors divert their allocations towards more appealing opportunities. We argue that it's time for investors to reconsider DeFi, especially by exploring innovative protocols and designs that could challenge incumbents in well-established markets. While it may not be revolutionary, these new DeFi protocols present an enticing chance to invest in lower-valued products capable of capturing market share from established players and introducing optimizations to reignite growth in the DeFi space. While a full-blown DeFi summer may not be imminent, there could be a hint of spring in the air.

While numerous opportunities exist within the DeFi landscape, this report will specifically delve into Gearbox and its undercollateralized lending, which we perceive as a particularly enticing prospect in the DeFi space. The primary focus will be on the anticipated growth in Total Value Locked (TVL) and Gearbox's potential to capitalize on this expansion. We identify a compelling opportunity driven by the financialization of points through liquid restaking tokens, which propelled Gearbox's TVL to quadruple since integration. As we transition into a bullish market, characterized by heightened competition among protocols and the emergence of market inefficiencies ripe for tokenized yield opportunities, we anticipate sustained growth for Gearbox TVL. Notably, Gearbox has a return on assets nearly seven times higher than traditional lending protocols, positioning it to capture a significant market share with just a fraction of the TVL.

The Bull Case for Onchain Lending

We identify three primary use cases for onchain lending:

  • Increasing Purchasing Power: The main utility and early product-market fit for lending protocols lie in the ability to leverage assets, thereby increasing onchain purchasing power. Users can boost their ETH (or other accepted collateral) exposure by borrowing against existing holdings or diversifying into new assets without liquidating their current positions.
  • Shorting Onchain: The provision to borrow assets opens up opportunities for onchain shorting, allowing users to capitalize on price declines.
  • Leveraged Yield Farming: Onchain lending introduces the prospect of leveraged yield farming, akin to the traditional carry trade, provided that the yield on the borrowed asset exceeds the borrowing costs.

Criticism of existing lending protocols

The lending space is currently dominated by Aave and Compound, holding 40% of the total value locked (TVL) share among lending protocols. While users can amplify their exposure by borrowing against crypto collateral, typically ETH, these protocols can only provide around a 70-80% loan-to-value (LTV) ratio to facilitate permissionless access. This results in overcollateralized loans, leading to suboptimal capital efficiency. Despite their capital inefficiency, these protocols experienced growth during the bull market as users sought to increase their crypto exposure through borrowing. However, the landscape of DeFi has evolved, and there are compelling reasons why these blue-chip lending protocols are no longer competitive in addressing the established lending use cases.

Displacement of Increasing Purchasing Power

Aave and Compound gained popularity during the previous bull run as a means to leverage assets for increased exposure. However, the current onchain market dynamics have introduced an abundance of onchain perpetual protocols, a trend not widespread during the last bull market. Perpetual protocols, despite higher trading costs, offer users significantly more leverage in competition with lending protocols. As perpetual protocols expand the breadth of assets they cover, there is a diminishing incentive for users to borrow using lending protocols. While there may be an opportunity to capture demand for altcoins not listed on perpetual exchanges, we anticipate that most of this volume will be seized by perpetual protocols integrated with Uniswap Hooks. To remain competitive, lending protocols must substantially increase their available LTV.

Infeasibility of Shorting

Lending protocols face difficulties entering the shorting market because they are limited to shorting assets that can be borrowed. The slow addition of new markets by lending protocols, focusing on the most liquid assets, makes it infeasible for them to capture a significant portion of this market. Establishing a shorting market would necessitate the rapid inclusion of new assets available for borrowing to address short demand not satisfied by perpetual trading protocols.

Inefficiency in Leveraged Yield Farming

Lending protocols also fall short of providing an efficient framework for leveraged yield farming. The low LTVs contribute to a suboptimal utilization of capital. For users seeking to borrow ETH to deploy in a new farm, the requirement to provide more collateral than they can borrow becomes a disincentive as the same strategy could be executed by farming with less ETH, thereby saving on borrowing costs. To address this inefficiency, raising LTVs and/or introducing new collateral types becomes essential, empowering users to leverage yield opportunities with both their collateral and the borrowed asset.

In summary, the shortcomings of lending protocols stem from three primary issues:

  • Low LTVs
  • A limited selection of borrowable assets
  • A narrow range of accepted collateral.

Alternative Models Emerging as Solutions

New lending models are stepping in to address the limitations of existing DeFi lending. These innovative approaches can be broadly categorized as undercollateralized lending and isolated pools.

Undercollateralized lending

Undercollateralized lending protocols allow borrowers to borrow up to 10x their collateral. However, there's a direct tradeoff between raising LTVs and expanding the range of acceptable assets. To facilitate undercollateralized loans (maximizing LTV), protocols must maintain control over both the collateral and the borrowed position to ensure liquidation if the borrowed position depreciates. This differs from traditional onchain lending, where users have unrestricted flexibility in deploying borrowed assets. Without control, permissioned systems with known counterparties would be necessary to prevent borrowers from absconding with borrowed assets and realizing immediate gains as the amount borrowed is greater than the provided collateral. Consequently, undercollateralized lending protocols need to be selective in the yield strategies borrowers can employ, limiting flexibility.

Isolated Pools

Isolated lending pools diverge from the Aave and Compound design by isolating liquidity and borrowing into distinct smart contracts. In this model, each pool allows one collateral type to be used for borrowing one specific asset, operating through a separate smart contract. By isolating risk to specific pools, these lending protocols can swiftly incorporate new strategies, as an exploit in one pool won't impact the rest of the protocol. This approach facilitates a broader array of assets, offering increased flexibility for borrowers who have a higher probability of using a yield-bearing asset as collateral, creating a genuine leveraged carry trade. Isolated lending pools maintain an overcollateralized model, but without restrictions on the use of borrowed assets. We are seeing the emergence of new protocols solely focused on isolated lending pools, as well as traditional DeFi protocols beginning to support isolated lending.

Many lending protocols still follow the traditional pooled risk approach, where liquidity is deposited into a single capital pool, meaning lenders bear equal risks of bad debt, regardless of the assets they supply. Recently, lending protocols like Aave, have adopted a hybrid approach by introducing isolated lending pools. These isolated pools allow borrowers to use a broader range of assets as collateral but often restrict them to borrowing stablecoins at lower LTV ratios. Notable protocols exclusively focused on isolated lending include Fraxlend and Morpho Blue, aiming to expand accepted collateral rapidly.

During the previous bullish market, most undercollateralized lending was semi-onchain. Liquidity could be deposited by anyone, but capital was borrowed by offchain entities, mainly trading firms with the protocol acting as a mediator between offchain and onchain entities. Fully onchain under collateralized lending platforms are now gaining momentum, with Gearbox leading the market with a 90% TVL share.

Beyond the scope of this report, there is a smaller niche of peer-to-peer lending protocols functioning as a marketplace for counterparty discovery. These platforms primarily address the very long-tail of assets, where borrowers seek counterparties to borrow against illiquid or volatile assets.

Liquid Restaking Case Study

The impact of different lending models on borrowed yield becomes evident when examining the case of Liquid Restaking Tokens, a prominent strategy among yield farmers. In this case study, we devised a hypothetical yield strategy where a user deploys one ETH of value into a lending protocol to borrow ETH. The borrowed ETH is then used to acquire eETH and accumulate EigenLayer points, which are subsequently sold on Whales Market over 18 weeks before repaying the loan. The chart below illustrates the yields generated by implementing the various strategies.

Scenario 1: Borrowing ETH on Aave using ETH as collateral

Key assumptions:

  • The borrower uses one ETH as collateral.
  • The borrower borrows at an LTV of 70%.
  • Borrow APY is 2.6%.
  • Average price of points on Whales Market is 0.00008 ETH.
  • The price of eETH:ETH is one.

Scenario 2: Borrowing ETH on Morpho Blue using eETH as collateral

Key assumptions:

  • The borrower uses one eETH as collateral.
  • The borrower borrows at an LTV of 70%.
  • Borrow APY is 13.80%.
  • Average price of points on Whales Market is 0.00008 ETH.
  • The price of eETH:ETH is one.

Scenario 3: Borrowing ETH on Gearbox using eETH as collateral

Key assumptions:

  • The borrower uses one ETH as collateral.
  • The borrower borrows 5 times their collateral.
  • Borrow APY is 20.85%.
  • Average price of points on Whales Market is 0.00008 ETH.
  • The price of eETH:ETH is 1.

The case study exposes inefficiencies in current lending models, as pursuing this strategy on Aave results in a lower return compared to executing the strategy without leverage. Including eETH as collateral enhances yields, offering real leverage as both the collateral and the borrowed asset generate returns. However, overcollateralization presents the highest return and is likely to attract greater usage from borrowers seeking integrated strategies.

Looking ahead, we anticipate onchain lending to predominantly occur in isolated pools or under collateralized lending platforms. However, we see a clearer upside for undercollateralized lending due to the market underestimating the total addressable market (TAM), overestimating growth constraints, and presenting greater differentiation from incumbents.

While the three primary use cases for onchain lending have been outlined, undercollateralized lending protocols may face limitations in competing for leveraged long or short positions. This is because these protocols need to explicitly incorporate new assets or strategies available to maintain control over borrowed position. This causes undercollateralized lending protocols to primarily focus on trading major assets, putting them in an unfavorable competition with onchain perpetual protocols for leveraged trading. As a result, their primary focus should be on the leveraged yield farming market.

Opportunity for Gearbox (GEAR)

In our opinion, the most enticing play to capitalize on an evolving lending landscape is the undercollateralized lending platform Gearbox. Gearbox has cornered a differentiated market with superior monetization compared to traditional lending markets and has an opportunity to capitalize on growth in onchain yield/points farming.

Cornering a differentiated market

While undercollateralized lending does directly compete with DeFi lending incumbents, these protocols require a completely different design, reducing the probability of incumbents launching a competing product. This differs from isolated pool protocols whose main point of differentiation is expanding the breadth of supported assets and not in design differentiation. We think there is a high probability that incumbents expand into an isolated/permissionless model to compete with existing isolated pool protocols in expanding asset breadth, meaning we see heightened competition for this market.

The undercollateralized lending market is contested by three protocols: Gearbox, Stella (founded by the same team as Alpha Homora), and Blueberry (pre-launch). Gearbox stands out as the market leader, with a TVL of over $130 million, representing a 90% share among the three protocols. Each protocol generates revenue through various borrowing cost mechanisms. Gearbox employs an explicit borrow APY, while Stella utilizes a pay-as-you-earn model where borrowers contribute a portion of their yield back to lenders.  Under collateralized lending likely benefits from first mover advantage, as lenders will trust the protocol with a longer history of security given lenders are the ones with capital at risk. This means Gearbox will likely maintain high market share, with competitors forced to differentiate by integrating riskier yield strategies or offering high incentive programs to attract LPs.

Superior monetization over incumbents

Under collateralized lending stands out for its higher return on assets compared to incumbent protocols. This stems from the incumbents' inability to capture a leveraged carry trade, leading to lower utilization and diminished borrowing rates. When combined with a presently lower protocol take rate, this contributes to a substantially lower return on assets.

As a concrete example, Aave V3 currently exhibits a return on supplied liquidity of 0.44%, over seven times lower than Gearbox’s 3%. This disparity in ROA is reflected in the FDV/TVL ratios, with Gearbox's FDV/TVL ratio roughly 8.25 times that of Aave.

The difference in ROA between Gearbox and Aave suggests that Gearbox could justify the same FDV as Aave, with only a fraction of the TVL. If incumbents broaden their asset breadth, their ROAs will likely rise near Gearbox's levels. The potential improvement in ROAs for existing players would come from meeting the demand for a carry trade by increasing the range of collateral assets, boosting utilization, and raising borrowing costs. However, any decline in Gearbox's superior monetization would stem from the appreciation of incumbents, not a deterioration in Gearbox's ROAs. Therefore, this scenario doesn't create a downside for Gearbox, positioning it favorably.

Total Addressable Market for TVL

Growth Restrictions

As an undercollateralized lending protocol, Gearbox has some growth limitations which we have outlined below.

Supply Constraints:

Under collateralized lending protocols will be primarily limited by Liquidity Providers' (LPs) willingness to lend assets. LPs bear the risk of putting capital at stake to enable undercollateralized loans. LPs take on additional risks beyond the smart contract and liquidity risks associated with traditional lending protocols; they also bear exposure to smart contract risks related to every protocol where borrowed assets are utilized. The added exposure to smart contract risks across every protocol where borrowed assets are employed means LPs will demand a higher return on capital, estimated to be 3x ETH stake rate, to compensate for this heightened risk.

Credibility Threshold:

Because of the increased risk for lenders, undercollateralized lending platforms are anticipated to integrate with credible protocols, measured through TVL. Currently, the smallest protocol integrated with the leading undercollateralized lending platform Gearbox is Yearn, with roughly $380 million TVL. We assume that any protocol under $300 million TVL has not achieved the credibility necessary for integration.

Integration Challenges:

Integrating yield farms meeting the specified TVL and Borrow Annual Percentage Yield (APY) criteria won't be instantaneous due to the associated overhead for undercollateralized lenders enabling new strategies. However, the distribution of opportunities meeting these criteria is top-heavy, with only ten pools accounting for 50% of opportunities by TVL. By integrating 20 pools, lending platforms can potentially capture just under 70% of addressable farms.

Growth Opportunities

Liquid Restaking Tokens

Gearbox's integration with LRTs has played a pivotal role in driving the growth of the protocol's TVL, which has more than quadrupled since the inclusion of eETH as a yield strategy. This proves liquid restaking as a fundamental use case for undercollateralized lending, expanding the risk spectrum and generating the higher yields sought by borrowers and essential for lenders.

However, a pertinent concern regarding LRTs in the context of Gearbox revolves around the sustainability of high yields post the EigenLayer airdrop as the speculation on airdrop value remains the primary source of LRT yield. A significant decrease in the value derived from staking within EigenLayer could trigger capital flight into alternative strategies, substantially reducing the addressable market for LRT carry trades. Nevertheless, we do not foresee substantial capital flight and anticipate EigenLayer TVL to remain stable.

We do not foresee capital flight due to a general lack of opportunity in generating high yields on ETH. Almost all ETH deposit strategies offer yields below 10%. In our perspective, providing EigenLayer stakers with a yield of approximately 10-15% should be adequate to maintain a stable TVL.

However, uncertainties persist regarding the sustainability of a 10-15% yield generated by Actively Validated Services (AVS) rewards. AVS's on EigenLayer will need to incentivize stakers to run validators, likely in the form of AVS token rewards. Notably, EigenLayer AVS's, unlike non-EigenLayer networks, won't have to compensate stakers for the price risk associated with exposure to the network's native asset. AVS's will solely need to provide incentives for running a validator, not holding a new token on the validator's balance sheet.

The ROI demanded by validators for offering validator services without price risk can be approximated by creating a delta-hedged staking position using ETH as collateral to borrow and short the asset being staked. The net yield from staking income minus borrowing costs can offer a rough estimate of the yield needed to incentivize validators. Based on these numbers, AVS's are expected to provide a rate similar to smaller proof-of-stake chains, around 8-12%.

In the initial months post the EigenLayer launch, AVS's will undergo a bootstrapping phase, making it infeasible for staking rewards to be paid solely from network activity. Instead, the yield offered by an AVS will be a function of AVS inflation and Market Capitalization. Assuming the combined Fully Diluted Valuation (FDV) of AVS's is approximately $10 billion, with an average inflation rate of 10%, it provides a floor yield of just under 10% to EigenLayer stakers. However, this yield could be significantly higher due to EigenLayer validators rehypothecating their stake across multiple AVS to earn boosted rewards as well as the potential to receive future airdrops, ensuring returns within our 10-15% target range to prevent capital flight.

Ethena

Gearbox has recently revealed its plans to incorporate support for USDe, presenting an additional pathway for TVL growth. Ethena's tokenized carry trade has demonstrated significant profitability within a short timeframe, propelling the protocol's TVL to over $830 million. We envision this market expanding for two key reasons.

Firstly, as the crypto markets experience appreciation, the aggregate open interest on ETH perpetuals also rises. This positive trend enhances the profitability of the carry trade while simultaneously elevating the TVL ceiling that Ethena can deploy without compromising the trade's profitability. In the event of entering a new bullish market, escalating prices are likely to boost open interest, tilting the long-short interest toward the long side. Consequently, this dynamic amplifies both the profitability and scalability of a tokenized carry trade.

Secondly, surging prices in the market create analogous carry-trade opportunities across assets. This presents an opportunity for Ethena or another tokenization protocol to integrate additional assets, expanding the scope for a tokenized carry trade product to scale even further. Furthermore, bullish markets may give rise to additional market inefficiencies that can potentially be tokenized, establishing an extra avenue for growth that can be harnessed by lending protocols.

General Yield

The third growth opportunity resembles traditional yield farming and ponzis that Gearbox can incorporate. We foresee an increase in these opportunities during the bull market, driven by heightened competition for attention and capital. As the bull market unfolds, we anticipate a surge in project launches, each vying for attention and capital in a competitive landscape. To stand out, many projects will create incentive schemes to financially reward user or capital participation. This trend presents an integration opportunity for Gearbox and a chance to further grow TVL.

Token Valuations Discussion

Our valuation methodology for projecting potential upside for GEAR involves forecasting TVL and applying the Return on Assets (ROA) to predict protocol revenues, followed by the application of an FDV/revenue multiple.

The growth in TVL is contingent on Gearbox's ability to enhance market penetration and capitalize on expanding opportunities in LRTs, Ethena, and General Yield. While we anticipate a stagnant total addressable market for LRTs, we project Gearbox's market share to increase slightly. Gearbox currently holds approximately 1.7% of the LRT market, but holds a market share of 3-6% for the LRTs it has integrated with. Our forecast predicts Gearbox's LRT share to rise to 2%.

The launch of Gearbox's Ethena integration on March 11th, 2024, provides limited historical data. Nonetheless, we estimate Gearbox capturing approximately 5% of Ethena TVL based on its share of integrated LRTs. Additionally, we anticipate a 75% growth in Ethena TVL, considering the market conditions previously described.

Approximately $37 million in Gearbox TVL is either idle or deployed in different DeFi strategies, categorized as general yield. We project a 75% increase in this value, assuming additional DeFi integrations are not captured by our LRT or Ethena forecasts.

As a result, we anticipate a 70% growth in Gearbox TVL, reaching approximately $230 million.

Utilizing forecasted TVL allows us to estimate Gearbox's ROA to project revenues. Following LRT integrations over the past few weeks, Gearbox has maintained an average ROA of around 3%, significantly higher than Aave’s 0.44%, attributed to higher utilization, borrow APY, and a higher protocol take-rate. However, we anticipate ROA to decrease to around 2.63%, aligning with a utilization of 60% and average borrowing costs of 15%.

Applying this to the forecasted TVL results in an annualized revenue of approximately $6 million. Employing Aave’s six-month FDV/TVL multiple of 48 to Gearbox revenues suggests a potential FDV of $291 million, representing 50% upside for the GEAR token.

Risks

Assumptions on TVL growth

Our optimism regarding undercollateralized lending hinges on the early stages of an extended crypto bull market. This is anticipated to stimulate the emergence of new yield farms and market inefficiencies for borrowers to exploit. Conversely, a lack of market growth may result in stagnant yields and a diminished TAM.

Assumptions about security

The nature of undercollateralized lending introduces heightened risks of bad debt, posing a potential obstacle to sustained growth.

Assumed differentiation

Our preference for undercollateralized lending over isolated pool lending protocols is founded on the distinct design space it occupies within DeFi. This uniqueness implies a lower likelihood of established lending protocols encroaching on this market.

Data risks

It's crucial to acknowledge potential data risks in our Gearbox forecasts, as they are derived from a relatively limited dataset spanning approximately one month. This short time frame could misrepresent the protocol's ability to monetize and capture TVL in either direction.

Closing Thoughts

While DeFi has been overshadowed by emerging crypto segments, the landscape is evolving with new protocols addressing the shortcomings of incumbents. This not only presents an opportunity to wrestle market share from established players but also to fuel overall DeFi market growth. One promising area of improvement is in lending markets, especially under collateralized lending, where users can leverage up to 10x by entrusting the protocol with both their collateral and borrowed position.

The introduction of LRTs has rekindled interest in speculative yield, the primary use case for onchain lending. The growth in this segment is poised to continue, particularly in a bull market where protocols are incentivizing users with high rewards, and market inefficiencies create additional yield opportunities.

Anticipating a 4-5x upside for onchain under collateralized leverage protocols, the potential for further gains exists if the TAM continues to expand. However, some of this growth is priced in as Gearbox trades on a FDV/revenue multiple of 70x compared to Aave’s 48x.
